@node "Intro" "MakeReadme: Introduction"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Main"
Make Readme arexx scripts for Thor and CygnusED

Û 1996 by Kenneth C. Nilsen. PUBLIC DOMAIN.

(Package version 1.1)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
INTRODUCTION


Don't you hate it.. everytime you shall upload a package to AmiNet you must
make those .readme files. Specially those headers which says Short: and so
on.

Well, I made these script to do some of that terrible terrible work (!) so I
can concentrate on the main text.

If you use @{"CygnusEd" link "CEDUSage" 0} or @{"Thor" link "ThorUsage" 0} this is the solution for you when you will make
readme files.

The scripts will prompt input requesters where you can give minimal data
about the program and optionally type and requirements. Then the program
will format a header with the data and your name (which is pre-programmed in
the scripts). The only thing you have to do is to write more specific about
the program below. Well, you can also make a default description too and you
don't have to write anything at all :-)

If you need the script for other packages than Thor and CygnusEd, please
send arexx documentation on the package you're using.

Also send suggestions and comments to my @{"address" link "Address" 0}.


Enjoy!
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "MakeReadme: Requirements"
@prev "Intro"
Make Readme arexx scripts for Thor and CygnusED

Û 1996 by Kenneth C. Nilsen. PUBLIC DOMAIN.

(Package version 1.1)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
REQUIREMENTS:


   What you need to run this arexx script:

        - RexxMast running
        - Thor 2.x or CygnusED 3.5+

   You also need to install the scripts correctly.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "ThorUsage" "MakeReadme: Usage from Thor"
@next "CEDUSage"
@prev "Requirements"
Make Readme arexx scripts for Thor and CygnusED

Û 1996 by Kenneth C. Nilsen. PUBLIC DOMAIN.

(Package version 1.1)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
USAGE FROM THOR:

      Installation
    ----------------

        Copy the MakeReadme.fse into Thor:rexx/fse/
        Start sys:utillities/RexxMast

        Start Thor and FSE
        Go the meny and choose a free line in the menu to install the
        script to

        When you now press the key or run the script from FSE menu, the
        script will prompt an input requester. You can now press cancel
        to interrupt (or press return).

        You can press <return> when you're asked about Program type and
        requirements. If so these lines will not be witten to the text.

        The cursor can be any where on the page when you start the script.
        The script will flow text from upper left.

        Save text as a .readme file.

        That's it!

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node "CEDUSage" "MakeReadme: Usage from CygnusED"
@prev "ThorUsage"
Make Readme arexx scripts for Thor and CygnusED

Û 1996 by Kenneth C. Nilsen. PUBLIC DOMAIN.

(Package version 1.1)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
USAGE FROM CYGNUSED:

      Installation
    ----------------

        Copy the MakeReadme.ced into Rexx:ced/
        Start sys:utillities/RexxMast

        Start CygnusEd.
        Go the meny and choose a free line in the menu to install the
        script to. Save definitions

        When you now press the key or run the script from CED menu, the
        script will prompt an input requester. You can now press cancel
        to interrupt (or press return).

        You can press <return> when you're asked about Program type and
        requirements. If so these lines will not be witten to the text.

        The cursor can be any where on the page when you start the script.
        The script will flow text from upper left.

        Save text as a .readme file.

        That's it!

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

